# Git: Commit & Push After Every Task

After completing **any code change**, always run the full git workflow:

## Workflow

```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "<type>(<scope>): <short description>"
git push origin HEAD
```

## Commit Message Format (Conventional Commits)

```
<type>(<scope>): <imperative, lowercase summary under 72 chars>

[optional body: explain WHY, not WHAT]
```

### Types

| Type | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature or screen |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code restructure, no behavior change |
| `style` | UI/CSS-only changes |
| `chore` | Deps, config, tooling |
| `db` | Migration, schema, RLS policy changes |
| `docs` | README, comments |

### Scopes (Nestlink-specific)

`web`, `mobile`, `supabase`, `core`, `auth`, `visitors`, `complaints`, `billing`, `amenities`, `guard`, `notifications`

## Examples

```bash
# New feature
git commit -m "feat(web): add global command-palette search"

# Bug fix
git commit -m "fix(mobile): correct OTP input max-length on Android"

# DB migration
git commit -m "db(supabase): add RLS policy for amenity_bookings"

# Multiple files, one scope
git commit -m "feat(visitors): generate QR pass and notify resident on creation"
```

## Rules

- **Never** skip push after implementing a feature — always `git push origin HEAD`
- If on a feature branch, push that branch: `git push origin <branch-name>`
- Include a body if the change is non-obvious or has trade-offs
- After pushing, confirm with: `git log --oneline -3`
